Introduction

Base URL: http://localhost

This documentation aims to provide all the information you need to work with our API.

As you scroll, you'll see code examples for working with the API in different programming languages in the dark area to the right (or as part of the content on mobile). You can switch the language used with the tabs at the top right (or from the nav menu at the top left on mobile).

Authenticating requests

This API is not authenticated.

Endpoints

Handle an incoming registration request.

Example request:
curl --request POST \
    "http://localhost/api/v1/register" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --header "Accept: application/json" \
    --data "{
    \"name\": \"bxmvjenmdbmqgsqqkj\",
    \"email\": \"barton.eva@example.net\",
    \"password\": \"animi\"
}"

const url = new URL(
    "http://localhost/api/v1/register"
);

const headers = {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Accept": "application/json",
};

let body = {
    "name": "bxmvjenmdbmqgsqqkj",
    "email": "barton.eva@example.net",
    "password": "animi"
};

fetch(url, {
    method: "POST",
    headers,
    body: JSON.stringify(body),
}).then(response => response.json());
Received response:
Request failed with error:


Tip: Check that you're properly connected to the network.
If you're a maintainer of ths API, verify that your API is running and you've enabled CORS.
You can check the Dev Tools console for debugging information.

Request      

POST api/v1/register

Headers

Content-Type      

Example: application/json

Accept      

Example: application/json

Body Parameters

name   string   

Must not be greater than 255 characters. Example: bxmvjenmdbmqgsqqkj

email   string   

Must be a valid email address. Must not be greater than 255 characters. Example: barton.eva@example.net

password   string   

Example: animi

Handle an incoming authentication request.

Example request:
curl --request POST \
    "http://localhost/api/v1/login" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --header "Accept: application/json" \
    --data "{
    \"email\": \"alanis.herzog@example.net\",
    \"password\": \"\\/\\\"n!hK,GC{C2fBt;f\"
}"

const url = new URL(
    "http://localhost/api/v1/login"
);

const headers = {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Accept": "application/json",
};

let body = {
    "email": "alanis.herzog@example.net",
    "password": "\/\"n!hK,GC{C2fBt;f"
};

fetch(url, {
    method: "POST",
    headers,
    body: JSON.stringify(body),
}).then(response => response.json());
Received response:
Request failed with error:


Tip: Check that you're properly connected to the network.
If you're a maintainer of ths API, verify that your API is running and you've enabled CORS.
You can check the Dev Tools console for debugging information.

Request      

POST api/v1/login

Headers

Content-Type      

Example: application/json

Accept      

Example: application/json

Body Parameters

email   string   

Must be a valid email address. Example: alanis.herzog@example.net

password   string   

Example: /"n!hK,GC{C2fBt;f

Handle an incoming new password request.

Example request:
curl --request POST \
    "http://localhost/api/v1/reset-password" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --header "Accept: application/json" \
    --data "{
    \"token\": \"aut\",
    \"email\": \"gail.hyatt@example.com\",
    \"password\": \"eligendi\"
}"

const url = new URL(
    "http://localhost/api/v1/reset-password"
);

const headers = {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Accept": "application/json",
};

let body = {
    "token": "aut",
    "email": "gail.hyatt@example.com",
    "password": "eligendi"
};

fetch(url, {
    method: "POST",
    headers,
    body: JSON.stringify(body),
}).then(response => response.json());
Received response:
Request failed with error:


Tip: Check that you're properly connected to the network.
If you're a maintainer of ths API, verify that your API is running and you've enabled CORS.

POST api/v1/reset-password

Headers

Content-Type      

Example: application/json

Accept      

Example: application/json

Body Parameters

token   string   

Example: aut

email   string   

Must be a valid email address. Example: gail.hyatt@example.com

Mark the authenticated user's email address as verified.

Example request:
curl --request GET \
    --get "http://localhost/api/v1/verify-email/reiciendis/enim" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --header "Accept: application/json"
const url = new URL(
    "http://localhost/api/v1/verify-email/reiciendis/enim"
);

const headers = {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Accept": "application/json",
};

fetch(url, {
    method: "GET",
    headers,
}).then(response => response.json());

Example response (401):

Show headers 
cache-control: no-cache, private
content-type: application/json
vary: Origin
 

{
    "message": "Unauthenticated."
}

If you're a maintainer of ths API, verify that your API is running and you've enabled CORS.
You can check the Dev Tools console for debugging information.

Request      

GET api/v1/verify-email/{id}/{hash}

Headers

Content-Type      

Example: application/json

Accept      

Example: application/json

URL Parameters

id   string   

The ID of the verify email. Example: reiciendis

hash   string   

Example: enim

GET api/v1/sub-departments

Example request:
curl --request GET \
    --get "http://localhost/api/v1/sub-departments" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --header "Accept: application/json"
const url = new URL(
    "http://localhost/api/v1/sub-departments"
);

const headers = {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Accept": "application/json",
};

fetch(url, {
    method: "GET",
    headers,
}).then(response => response.json());

GET api/v1/loan-types

Example request:
curl --request GET \
    --get "http://localhost/api/v1/loan-types" \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --header "Accept: application/json"

    "http://localhost/api/v1/loan-types"
);

const headers = {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Accept": "application/json",
};

    method: "GET",
    headers,
}).then(response => response.json());
